# Cursor Rules for excel-addin

## Repository Overview
- Office taskpane add-in named Workbook Copilot with Python FastAPI backend in `backend/app` and React + TypeScript frontend in `frontend`.
- Backend exposes REST endpoints (`/health`, `/providers`, `/chat`) and relies on provider integrations defined in `providers.py`.
- Frontend uses Office.js APIs and expects the backend at `https://localhost:8000` by default.

## Backend (Python 3.11, FastAPI)
- Prefer async FastAPI endpoints and keep request/response models in `schemas.py`.
- Centralize configuration in `config.py` using `pydantic.Settings`; read environment variables via `get_settings()`.
- Register new orchestrator logic in `orchestrator.py`; extend `LangGraphOrchestrator` rather than creating ad-hoc flows.
- Honor logging patterns already in place (`logging.getLogger(__name__)`).
- Keep provider definitions in `providers.py`; new providers should implement `BaseProvider` and be added to `available_providers()`.
- Run locally with `python -m uvicorn app.main:app --reload --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000` (add SSL flags when Excel requires HTTPS).

## Frontend (React + TypeScript)
- Use functional components; colocate styles in `taskpane.css` or CSS modules if added later.
- Keep provider options and API URLs in `config.ts`; expose types via `types.ts`.
- Use Office.js patterns already established in `excel.ts`; avoid blocking UI thread—delegate long tasks to backend.
- npm scripts: `npm start` for dev, `npm run build` for production. Trust certificates using `npm run dev:cert` if HTTPS issues arise.

## Documentation Standards
- **All code must include production-level docstrings and comments.**
- Python: Use Google-style or NumPy-style docstrings for all classes, functions, and methods. Include:
  - Clear description of purpose
  - Parameter types and descriptions (`Args:` section)
  - Return type and description (`Returns:` section)
  - Raises section for exceptions
  - Examples for complex functions
- TypeScript/JavaScript: Use JSDoc comments for all exported functions, classes, and interfaces. Include:
  - `@description` for purpose
  - `@param` with types for all parameters
  - `@returns` with return type and description
  - `@throws` for error conditions
- Add inline comments for non-obvious logic, complex algorithms, business rules, and workarounds.
- Document "why" not just "what" - explain reasoning behind implementation choices when non-trivial.
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes; remove outdated comments.

## Testing & Quality
- Provide unit tests where feasible (Python: `pytest`; TypeScript: add tests under `frontend/src/__tests__` when necessary).
- Maintain type hints across Python code, keep FastAPI response models explicit.
- Prefer ESLint and Prettier defaults defined in `.eslintrc.json` and project config.

## Git & Repo Hygiene
- First get the changes in files reviewed by the user before commiting and pushing them to git repo.
- Do not commit secrets or local environment files (`.env`, `manifest.md`, certs are ignored).
- When adding dependencies, update respective lockfiles (`requirements.txt`, `package-lock.json`).
- Document major changes in `README.md` or dedicated docs if added.
- Always track GITSHA after every meaningful task completion.
- Add it to the enhancements.md as a Phase Checkpoint.
- Reference these SHAs when debugging, testing, or asking AI to resume from previous states.
